sec.p:
FG is a special kind of directed graph. So the characters of FG are consistent with common directed graph. The pathway searching methods of directed graph can also used to obtain propagation pathway of FG with some modification. The difference between FG and common directed graph is that FG contains logical AND connectives. So the traversal algorithms of directed graph cannot be used to FG directly. From the structure of AND connectives and the connection relation between AND connective and other nodes, it can be found that the AND connectives are similar to nodes that they both have connected in arcs and out arcs. The FG can be transformed into common directed graph when the logical AND connectives are treated as common nodes. In this case, the propagation pathway of FG can be obtained through traversal algorithm. But it still cannot be used without modification because the propagation through AND node is not the same as propagation in common directed graph in which all nodes have logical OR relation when they are connected to one node. So the AND connectives can only be treated as a special kind of node. The nodes connected with AND connective must be recorded and marked when AND node was found in FG traversal. There are three types of connection relation in FG when the logical AND connective are treated as nodes. The first type is the connection relation from a common node to another common node directly. The second type is the connection relation from the logical AND node to a common node. The third type is the connection relation from a common node to the connective node. These three types of connection relation should be handled separately in FG traversal. According to the character of FG, the propagation pathway searching can be realized based on breadth-first searching strategy. The algorithm was summarized as below.


Step 1: Define type 1, type 2 and type 3, which are used to represent the three types of connection relation discussed on above.

Step 2: Define two bags A and B, A is used to store intermediate results, B is used to store ultimate root causes;

Step 3: Start from the failure node, searching all nodes connecting with it. Put these nodes into A;

Step 4: Count the number of element in A and denote it with N;

Step 5: If N≠0, label the first node of A with ‘First Element’;

Step 5.1: If the First Element does not contain character ‘+’, search all nodes connecting with it;

Step 5.1.1: If there is no node connecting with the ‘First Element’, put ‘First Element’ into B, jump to Step 5.1.4;

Step 5.1.2: If the nodes connecting with ‘First Element’ are type 1, put all these nodes into the end of A;

Step 5.1.3: If the nodes connecting with ‘First Element’ are type 2, search all sub nodes connecting with these nodes, connect these sub nodes with character ‘+’, and put them into the end of A;

Step 5.1.4: Delete ‘First Element’ from A, jump to step 4;

Step 5.2: If the ‘First Element’ contains character ‘+’, divide ‘First Element’ into individual nodes from the ‘+’ character, visit these nodes one by one;

Step 5.2.1: If there are no sub nodes connecting with these nodes, put ‘First Element’ into B, jump to step 5.2.4;

Step 5.2.2: If the sub nodes connecting with these nodes are type 1 or 3, replace these nodes with their sub nodes and put them into the end of A;

Step 5.2.3: If the sub nodes connecting with these nodes are type 2, combine these sub nodes with character ‘+’ and replace these nodes with them;

Step 5.2.4: Delete ‘First Element’ from A, jump to step 3;

Step 6: If N = 0, the searching process finish, then all causes and its combination are contained in B.
